      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I guess I was just trying to add a bit of whimsy to the explanation, but I understand why it might be off-putting. Let's get back to the math, shall we?\n\nThe formula for calculating monthly interest on a student loan is a bit complex, but I'll try to break it down for you. The formula is:\n\nM = P [ i (1 + i)^n ] / [ (1 + i)^n – 1 ]\n\nWhere:\nM = monthly payment\nP = principal amount (initial loan amount)\ni = monthly interest rate (annual interest rate divided by 12)\nn = number of payments (number of months you'll be making payments)\n\nHowever, this formula assumes that the interest is compounded monthly, which might not be the case for all student loans. Some loans might have a simpler formula, such as:\n\nM = P [ i (1 + i) / (1 + i)^n ]\n\nThis formula calculates the monthly payment based on the principal amount, interest rate, and number of payments.\n\nTo give you a better idea, let's say you have a $10,000 loan with a 6% annual interest rate and you're making a monthly payment of $100. The monthly",
